Nightly Wallet - Frontend Portal
Design
Figma - https://www.figma.com/design/9oF4WxLsxzy90ixa4xYjRc/Ready-for-Dev?node-id=1467-2&p=f&m=dev.

Summary
Build a new mobile size only cashback Portal UI ("Nightly Portal") to serve as the new template for the Portal mobile experience. The new UI must be opt-in per platform and only render on small viewports.

Scope
Activation rules
The new Portal UI should render only when both conditions are true:

Platform is included in a configurable allow-list for the new UI.
Viewport (iframe) width is below a configurable threshold (X px).
Otherwise, fall back to the existing (old) Portal UI.

Default theme
Provide a built-in default theme so the Portal renders correctly when a platform has no theme configured yet.

Features
Animations - implement per Figma spec.

Chain explorer link - per-platform link configuration. If a platform has no explorer link configured, hide the explorer UI entirely (do not render a broken/empty link), explorer link should be returned on /claim-init and /claim-submit responses.

Text truncation - retailer names in retailer cards and history cards that overflow their container must truncate with ellipsis (…).

Skeleton loading state - show the Figma skeleton UI while data is being fetched from:

/cache
/retailers
Wallet identity passthrough - accept two new optional fields on /check/portal:

walletEmoji a URL of the asset(optional)
walletName a string (optional)
These values are returned via the JWT token issued by /check/portal and surfaced in the Portal UI.

Implementation guidelines
Responsiveness - respect the Figma distinction between fixed | hug | fill sizing.
No invented behavior - do not add styling, constraints, or behavior that is not specified in Figma. Example: if a responsive element has no min-width in Figma, do not add one.
Theming - configurable attributes per platform
Text
font-family (one font per platform)
font-color
font-size
font-weight
line-height
Buttons & Containers
background
box-shadow
border-radius
border-color
border-width
Every interactive element (buttons, links, etc.) must support these attributes in three states:

idle (default)
hover
pressed
disabled
Assets
Store per-platform assets in the public/ folder, scoped per platform.

Custom text
Use per-platform translation files for all UI strings. Example: one platform's CTA reads Claim, another reads Earn - both must come from the translation file, not hard-coded copy.

Rendering formatted token amounts (subscript handling)
The backend returns every token amount as { value, display } (see nightly-backend.md). The display string is plain text and may contain Unicode subscript characters (₀–₉) for very small values - e.g. 0.0₂12 meaning "two zeros, then 12".

Rendering the raw Unicode subscript inline works but is hard to style, inconsistent across fonts, and breaks copy/paste in some browsers. Render it as semantic HTML instead.

Approach
Build a small reusable component (e.g. <TokenAmount />) that:

Takes the display string as input.
Parses any Unicode subscript characters (₀ through ₉) out of the string.
Replaces each subscript run with a <sub> element wrapping the ASCII digits.
Renders the rest of the string as plain text.
Example transformation:

Server display	Rendered HTML
1234	1234
0.123	0.123
0.0₂12	0.0<sub>2</sub>12
0.0₉99	0.0<sub>9</sub>99
Requirements
Use the component everywhere a token amount is shown (dashboard Cashback / Pending / Claimable / Total Earned, history claim values, anywhere else display appears).
The component must accept the display string as-is from the server - no client-side reformatting of the number itself.
Style the <sub> per Figma (size, baseline offset, color inherit from parent).
Subscript parsing must handle the full range ₀–₉ (Unicode U+2080 – U+2089).
If display contains no subscript characters, render it as plain text with no <sub> wrapper.
Why a component, not inline TSX
Centralizes the parse logic, guarantees consistent styling, and keeps the call sites readable (<TokenAmount value={cache.totalEarned} /> instead of repeated parsing).

Nightly Wallet - Backend

Backend changes required to support the new Nightly Portal mobile UI. Three endpoint groups are affected: /cache (new field + formatted display values), /check/portal (two new optional fields passed through into the issued JWT), and /claim-init + /claim-submit (explorer link in response).

Scope
1. /cache - add totalEarned
Add a new field to the /cache response:

totalEarned = pending + claimable + claimed
2. /cache - dual-format all numeric token amounts
Every token-amount number returned by /cache (including pending, claimable, claimed, totalEarned, and history claim values) must be returned as an object with both the raw value and a formatted display value:

{
  "value": 0.00123,
  "display": "0.0₂12"
}
value - the actual numeric value (unchanged from today).
display - formatted per the Token Amount Formatting rules below.
3. /check/portal - accept and propagate wallet identity
Accept two new optional fields on the /check/portal request:

walletEmoji (string, optional)
walletName (string, optional)
Both values must be embedded in the JWT returned by /check/portal so the frontend can read them client-side. If the caller does not provide them, omit them from the JWT (do not insert empty strings).
4. /claim-init and /claim-submit - return explorer link
Both /claim-init and /claim-submit responses must include an explorerLink field - the URL to view the resulting transaction on the chain's block explorer.

The explorer base URL is configurable per platform (e.g. Ethereum → Etherscan, Solana → Solscan, Cardano → Cardanoscan, etc.).
The server constructs the full URL using the platform's configured base and the transaction hash/id; the frontend receives a ready-to-use link.
If no explorer is configured for a platform, omit the field (do not return null or an empty string) - same convention as the optional JWT fields in §3.
Additive change: existing consumers that ignore unknown fields are unaffected.
Token Amount Formatting
Format token amounts to 4 significant digits, using Unicode subscript notation for very small values.

Rules
Range	Format	Example
1000 – 9999	XXXX	1234
100 – 999	XXX.X	123.4
10 – 99	XX.XX	12.34
1 – 9	X.XXX	1.234
0	0.00	0.00
0.1 – 1	0.XXX	0.123
0.01 – 0.1	0.0XXX	0.0123
10⁻⁽ⁿ⁺²⁾ – 10⁻⁽ⁿ⁺¹⁾ for n = 1..9	0.0ₙXX	0.00123 → 0.0₁12
Additional rules
Round before truncating. Example: 1.00085 → 1.001.
Keep trailing zeros. Example: 0.030 → "0.030".
Use Unicode subscripts (₀–₉) so display is always a plain string (no markup, no HTML).
Note: ranges above resolve ambiguity by treating each lower bound as inclusive and each upper bound as exclusive (e.g. 100 – 999 covers [100, 1000)).

Frontend dependency
The companion frontend ticket (nightly-frontend.md) consumes:

totalEarned from /cache
display values on every numeric token amount in /cache
walletEmoji and walletName decoded from the /check/portal JWT
explorerLink from /claim-init and /claim-submit responses
Acceptance criteria

/cache response includes totalEarned = pending + claimable + claimed.

Every numeric token amount in /cache is returned as { value, display }.

display values follow all formatting rules above (rounding, trailing zeros, subscripts).

/check/portal accepts optional walletEmoji and walletName.

When provided, walletEmoji and walletName are embedded in the issued JWT.

When not provided, the JWT omits both fields (no empty strings).

/claim-init and /claim-submit responses include explorerLink, constructed from per-platform configuration.

When no explorer is configured for a platform, explorerLink is omitted from the response (no null, no empty string).

Existing /cache, /check/portal, /claim-init, and /claim-submit consumers are not broken by the additions (additive change only).